<br>
As to good keyboards, get an IBM.  They're thick and heavy and have a substantial click(noisy too), but they have big enter keys, generously sized regular keys, and can take one hell of a pounding.  I've had a number of keyboards give out on me over the years, sometimes seemingly for no reason, but IBM's really hold up well.  They're pricey too--usually like 70 to 100 bucks.  <br>
<br>
I'm not sure they even sell them anymore, but as a primary way you communicate with your computer, they're as important to me as a good mouse or monitor or sound card.  If the interface is off--you really feel it, and a good one really helps.  A good keyboard takes more abuse than anything, so to me it's worth the price. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ussyn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ssyn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk-in-Training</span><br>  Posts: 91<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(8/5/02 12:11:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: My keyboard setup</span><hr size=1> I couldn't imagine pulling without mouselook. Might as well play in 3rd person with your up/down world being so keyboard driven. Yuk.....<br>
